    <stitle>Spanish - Gu&#237;a para Localizaci&#243;n de Fallas del Sistema El&#233;ctrico - 3200, 4200, 4300, 4400,
        7300, 7400, 7500, 8500, 8600 - STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, TILT - 9600, 9700, 9800 - DISASSEMBLE - UNIVERSAL
        JOINTS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="3">
        <title>UNIVERSAL JOINTS</title>
        <para>The universal joints at the steering column end yoke and slip shaft may be removed at the steering gear
            and serviced separately.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Take care not to damage any bearing surfaces, especially the plastic-coated slip shaft.</para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place the universal joint in a vise (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501020">Figure 20</hotlnk>). Remove the snap rings fitting in the grooves of the
                spider bearings by pushing against the open end of the ring with a screwdriver.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0501020" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0501020" filename="../figg05/g0501020.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 16. Snap Ring Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                <callout1>3. SPIDER</callout1>
                <callout1>4. SNAP RING</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To prevent eye injury, safety glasses should be worn at all times when assembling or disassembling
                    components.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clamp the shaft assembly firmly in a vise with the yoke just clearing the vise, and the
                other yoke and shaft suspended with the bearing to be removed facing down (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501021">Figure 21</hotlnk>). Using a soft hammer, tap the yoke beside the bearing to
                be removed. The bearing should walk out.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0501021" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0501021" filename="../figg05/g0501021.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 17. Bearing Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the bearing does not come completely out, clamp the bearing in a vise.
                <emph type="bold">Use copper jaw covers</emph>. Using a soft hammer, strike the yoke driving it away
                from the bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501022">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0501022" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0501022" filename="../figg05/g0501022.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 18. Bearing Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With the bearings removed, the spider can easily be removed from the yoke.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
